  "opinion": "As a mechanic who’s spent decades working on cars and engines, I’ve seen how stereotypes can quietly undermine people in technical fields. Stereotype threat isn’t just a classroom concept—it’s real life. When someone from a group that’s historically been underrepresented in STEM, like girls or people of color, hears that ‘girls aren’t good at math,’ their brains start to race. They might second-guess their own abilities, even when they’re capable. I remember a young woman at my shop who was hesitant to fix a car because she thought she’d ‘mess it up.’ It wasn’t about skill—it was about fear. This isn’t just an academic issue; it’s about trust. We should address it by creating environments where people feel safe to try without judgment. For me, that means mentoring young women and people of color in trades, showing them that their worth isn’t tied to a single test or a textbook. In my community, I’ve started a volunteer program where we fix cars together, and it’s changed how people see themselves. Stereotype threat is a barrier that needs to be broken, not ignored. It’s not about changing people—it’s about changing the way we see them. If we can build trust and confidence in the hands of those who’ve been overlooked, we’ll see more people thrive in STEM fields. It’s a simple idea, but it’s one that takes patience and care to put into action.",
